  "slug": "disclosure-day-is-steven-spielbergs-true-believer-manifesto-",
  "title": "'Disclosure Day' Is Steven Spielberg's True Believer Manifesto. Kneel!",
  "show": "The Big Picture",
  "network": "The Ringer",
  "hosts": [
    "Sean Fennessey",
    "Amanda Dobbins"
  ],
  "published": "2026-06-12",
  "runtimeMin": 122,
  "format": "Sean and Amanda review Steven Spielberg's 'Disclosure Day,' the David Koepp-scripted alien-conspiracy chase that drops the metaphor and asks, flatly, what if they're real. First, a news rundown: the 'Social Reckoning' and 'Whale Fall' trailers and the Academy's Governors Awards honorees.",
  "segments": [
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "The news rundown",
      "note": "trailers and the Governors Awards",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "The Social Reckoning",
          "year": 2026,
          "note": "Aaron Sorkin's written-and-directed follow-up to 'The Social Network,' effectively a sequel. Jeremy Strong as Zuckerberg, Jeremy Allen White and Mikey Madison as reporter and whistleblower. The trailer even borrows the Reznor/Ross scoring though the two aren't on the film. Both hosts read it as a movie about a system, not a person, and don't expect much."
        },
        {
          "title": "Whale Fall",
          "year": 2026,
          "note": "The survival film from Daniel Kraus's novel, a man swallowed by a whale; Josh Brolin and Austin Abrams. Sean and Amanda saw the clip at CinemaCon and are pumped. Kraus just won a Pulitzer, though for 'Angel Down,' not this."
        },
        {
          "title": "Once Upon a Time in Harlem",
          "year": 2026,
          "note": "David and William Greaves documentary, 50 years in the making, on a reunion of Harlem Renaissance figures. Neon; caught at Cannes after a Sundance premiere. Sean calls it the presumptive Best Documentary favorite."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "review",
      "heading": "'Disclosure Day'",
      "note": "Spielberg goes literal — spoilers within",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Disclosure Day",
          "year": 2026,
          "note": "Spielberg's 35th feature: his own story, David Koepp's script (their fifth together), John Williams's score (their 30th), Kaminski shooting. Emily Blunt as a Kansas City weather reporter who reads minds and speaks an alien tongue; Josh O'Connor as a Wardex hacker sitting on proof of an 80-year alien cover-up, racing to broadcast it. Colin Firth as the villain Scanlan, Colman Domingo as the fixer, Eve Hewson as the girlfriend, Wyatt Russell as the boyfriend. A 70s-style conspiracy chase with no metaphor underneath: what if aliens are just real. Sean transcends; Amanda admires the set pieces at a remove. Both open the Emily Blunt Oscar campaign, and both flag the underwritten O'Connor role and a too-fast final act."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Age of Disclosure",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "The UAP documentary both hosts watched going in: ex-military and government talking heads, Marco Rubio among them, framing alien contact as a national-security threat. Credible on the facts, they thought, propagandistic in its hawkishness."
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
